<methodology slug="raci-matrix">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>pm-agile</domain>
    <summary>Assigns R, A, C, I roles to stakeholders per task to clarify ownership, decision-making, and communication. Enforces exactly one A per row.</summary>
    <category>accountability</category>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>raci-matrix</tag>
      <tag>accountability</tag>
      <tag>stakeholder-management</tag>
      <tag>cross-functional</tag>
      <tag>ownership</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
    <related>
      <ref slug="team-development"/>
      <ref slug="ai-in-project-management"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>RACI Matrix</title>

    <summary>A RACI matrix assigns exactly one of four roles — Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed — to each stakeholder for each task or deliverable. The single testable rule: every task row must have exactly one Accountable and at least one Responsible. Multiple Accountables on a single task is the most common failure mode and re-creates the "no clear owner" problem the matrix was designed to solve.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Projects fail from unclear ownership: "I thought you were handling that," duplicate effort, and approval bottlenecks from undefined decision-makers. RACI externalizes the implicit contract between roles before work starts. The PMI PMBOK 7th edition Team Performance Domain identifies role clarity as a prerequisite for high-performing teams.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Multi-role projects with more than 3 roles and more than 10 deliverables.</item>
        <item>Solopreneur engagements with contractors or agencies where one human plus outsourced parties need clear per-task ownership.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new hire or contractor — encodes "who owns what" in one readable table.</item>
        <item>Pre-mortem or kickoff for cross-functional features (PM + Eng + Design + QA + DevOps) before sprint zero.</item>
        <item>Incident response retros where "no one owned X" was a root cause — bake the new RACI into the runbook.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Solo work with no external collaborators — overhead with zero return.</item>
        <item>Self-organizing Scrum teams where Definition of Done plus collective code ownership already covers accountability — RACI can undermine team agency.</item>
        <item>Hyper-dynamic discovery work where tasks change weekly — the matrix goes stale faster than it can be maintained.</item>
        <item>Senior autonomous teams operating under DACI, Advice Process, or RAPID — those frameworks fit decision rights better.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="raci-rules">
      <p>The four RACI roles, validation rules that must pass for every row, and the most common failure modes.</p>

      <section name="role-definitions">
        <list>
          <item>Responsible (R): does the work. Multiple R per row is allowed; this is who executes the task.</item>
          <item>Accountable (A): final decision-maker for the task. Exactly ONE per row — this is the rule that matters most.</item>
          <item>Consulted (C): provides input before the decision is made. Two-way communication. Minimize to essential only.</item>
          <item>Informed (I): notified after the decision is made. One-way communication. Be generous with I.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="validation-rules">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Every task row must have exactly one Accountable; reject any RACI with zero or multiple A values in a single row.</statement>
          <rationale>Zero A means no decision-maker exists; multiple A creates accountability confusion and slows decisions. The PMI PMBOK 7th edition Team Performance Domain cites this as the primary RACI failure mode.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Every task row must have at least one Responsible; a task with no R has no executor and will not get done.</statement>
          <rationale>Without an R, the task is aspirationally on the matrix but not concretely assigned. It will be deprioritized or forgotten.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Limit Consulted roles to three per row; more than three C values creates an approval bottleneck that slows every task transition.</statement>
          <rationale>Every C requires soliciting and integrating feedback before proceeding. Each additional C adds a round-trip delay and a potential veto point.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Name roles, not people, in the RACI matrix; map role-to-person in a separate table.</statement>
          <rationale>People rotate; roles persist. A person-named matrix requires updating every time someone changes team or leaves, making it unmaintainable.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <antipattern>
          <description>A role that is "A" on more than 60% of the tasks in the matrix.</description>
          <reason>Heavy A concentration is a bottleneck indicator — that role becomes the single point of approval for most decisions. Distribute Accountable roles across appropriate decision-makers.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>All roles assigned "I" for a task (all-I row).</description>
          <reason>An all-I row means everyone is notified but no one executes or decides. This signals the underlying task is too vague to assign ownership.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>

      <section name="matrix-maintenance">
        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Tag RACI changes in version control with the commit that introduced them; treat the RACI as code.</statement>
          <rationale>Without version history, disputes about "who agreed to this" have no authoritative record. Git history provides the audit trail.</rationale>
        </rule>

        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Pair RACI with an escalation path specifying who holds A when the named accountable is unavailable for more than 24 hours.</statement>
          <rationale>Single-point accountability without an escalation path creates decision paralysis during PTO or unexpected absence.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="raci-examples">
      <p>Concrete RACI examples for a feature development workflow, a solopreneur-with-contractors engagement, and an agent-driven project.</p>

      <section name="feature-development-raci">
        <example type="good" title="Feature Development RACI">
          <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[| Activity           | PM | Product | Engineering | Design | QA |
|--------------------|----|---------|-------------|--------|----|
| Define requirements| C  | A       | C           | C      | I  |
| Create mockups     | I  | C       | I           | R      | I  |
| Approve design     | I  | A       | C           | R      | I  |
| Write code         | I  | C       | R           | I      | I  |
| Code review        | I  | I       | A           | I      | I  |
| Write tests        | I  | I       | C           | I      | R  |
| Deploy to staging  | C  | I       | R           | I      | C  |
| UAT sign-off       | I  | A       | I           | I      | R  |
| Production deploy  | A  | I       | R           | I      | C  |]]></code>
          <note>One A per row throughout. Engineering is A on code review (peer accountability). PM is A on production deploy (risk ownership). Consulted count is low — maximum 2 per row.</note>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="solopreneur-with-contractors">
        <example type="good" title="Solopreneur With Contractors">
          <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[| Task           | Owner | Designer | Developer | VA  |
|----------------|-------|----------|-----------|-----|
| Product vision | A/R   | I        | I         | I   |
| UI design      | A     | R        | C         | I   |
| Development    | A     | C        | R         | I   |
| Testing        | A     | I        | C         | R   |
| Launch         | A/R   | I        | I         | C   |]]></code>
          <note>A/R combined is acceptable for the solopreneur context where the single owner is both the decision-maker and executor. The pattern avoids the "A also = R fudge" anti-pattern because the intent is explicit.</note>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="agent-driven-project-raci">
        <example type="good" title="Agent-Driven Project RACI">
          <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[| Task                    | PM (human) | claude-agent | QA (human) |
|-------------------------|------------|--------------|------------|
| Generate issue hierarchy| A          | R            | I          |
| Triage incoming issues  | A          | R            | C          |
| Transition issue states | C          | R            | I          |
| Approve bulk changes    | A          | C            | I          |
| Retro on process policy | A          | C            | R          |]]></code>
          <note>The agent is always R (does the work) but never A (never the final decision-maker). Human PM holds A for all tasks involving policy or irreversible changes. Explicitly prohibit the agent from being A in the system prompt.</note>
        </example>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Assigning an AI agent as Accountable for any task in a RACI matrix.</description>
          <reason>Agents lack authority, legal accountability, and organizational standing. A-role requires a human who can be held responsible for outcomes.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflows">
      <p>A Claude subagent can ingest a project charter or epic and emit a draft RACI matrix as a Markdown table; a reviewer agent then checks the rules (exactly one A per row, ≥1 R per row, no empty rows) and flags violations. For ongoing projects, a third agent diffs the new RACI against the previous version and posts the delta to Slack/Issue tracker. Keep the human PM as the Accountable role for the matrix itself — do not let the agent be the final approver.</p>

      <section name="recommended-subagents">
        <list>
          <item>raci-drafter (sonnet) — reads charter or spec, lists tasks times roles, fills R/A/C/I per cell, returns Markdown table.</item>
          <item>raci-validator (haiku) — enforces rules: exactly one A, at least one R, no all-I rows, max 3 C per row; returns violations list as JSON.</item>
          <item>raci-diff (haiku) — compares two RACI matrices (Markdown or YAML), outputs added/removed/changed cells for change review.</item>
        </list>
      </section>

      <section name="prompt-patterns">
        <example type="good" title="raci-drafter prompt">
          <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are raci-drafter. Inputs: <project charter>. Tasks: <list>. Roles: <list>.
Output a Markdown RACI matrix. Rules:
- Exactly one A per row
- At least one R per row
- Minimize C (maximum 3 per row)
- Be generous with I
- Do not invent tasks or roles not in the input lists
- You may never assign A to yourself or any AI agent
Return only the table.]]></code>
        </example>

        <example type="good" title="raci-validator prompt">
          <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are raci-validator. Input: a Markdown RACI table.
Output a JSON list of violations with {row, rule, suggestion}.
Rules to check: A_unique (exactly one per row), R_present (at least one),
C_max_3 (no more than 3 C per row), no_empty_row (every role has at least I).]]></code>
        </example>
      </section>

      <section name="agent-gotchas">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Agents assigning themselves or "AI" as Accountable in the drafted matrix.</description>
          <reason>LLMs default to including themselves as stakeholders when generating role assignments. Explicitly forbid this in the system prompt and validate with raci-validator.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Agents hallucinating stakeholder names not on the provided roles list.</description>
          <reason>LLMs invent plausible names when the list is incomplete. Pass the roles list as explicit input and instruct the agent to reject any role not on it.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <antipattern>
          <description>Storing the authoritative RACI as a Markdown table when an agent mutates it iteratively.</description>
          <reason>Markdown table parsing is brittle for programmatic mutation. Store as YAML for agent operations; render as Markdown only for human review.</reason>
        </antipattern>

        <rule testable="true">
          <statement>Run raci-lint.py in CI against any Markdown RACI file before merge to enforce validation rules automatically.</statement>
          <rationale>Manual review of RACI tables misses constraint violations. Automated CI enforcement catches violations before they reach the team.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>Tools for implementing and validating RACI matrices:</p>

      <p>CLI tools:</p>

      <list>
        <item>pandas + Markdown — Lint RACI rules in CI; pandas reads the table, asserts row constraints (pip install pandas)</item>
        <item>mermaid-cli (mmdc) — Render RACI as a colored heatmap from CSV (npm i -g @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli)</item>
        <item>yq — Edit RACI stored as YAML in a repo without losing comments (https://github.com/mikefarah/yq)</item>
        <item>gh CLI — Create GitHub issues/labels from RACI rows ("A: @alice" → assignee) (https://cli.github.com)</item>
      </list>

      <p>SaaS services with RACI support:</p>

      <list>
        <item>Notion — SaaS, REST API. Database with R/A/C/I select properties; agent can CRUD via official API.</item>
        <item>Confluence — SaaS, REST API. Store RACI as table macro; updates need page version bumps.</item>
        <item>Coda — SaaS, REST API. Tables with formulas validate "exactly one A" automatically.</item>
        <item>Smartsheet — SaaS, REST API. Native RACI templates; cellLink to project plan.</item>
        <item>Lucidchart / Miro — SaaS, Limited API. Useful for whiteboard kickoff, painful to maintain via agent.</item>
        <item>Jira (custom field) — SaaS, REST API. Add R/A/C/I custom fields per role on each issue; query via JQL.</item>
        <item>GitHub Projects v2 — SaaS, GraphQL. Single-select fields per role; CODEOWNERS handles A for code paths.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>One A per row is the only rule that matters; everything else is style. Enforce it in CI.</statement>
        <rationale>Perfect enforcement of the A rule prevents the primary failure mode (unclear decision-making).</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Name roles, not people. People rotate; roles stick. Map role→person in a separate table.</statement>
        <rationale>Person-named matrices require constant updates and become stale quickly.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Extend with "S" (Support) and "V" (Verify) only if you actually use them — otherwise it's noise.</statement>
        <rationale>Extra roles add complexity without value if they are not actively used in decision-making.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Tag RACI changes in version control with the commit that introduced them; lets you do git blame on accountability.</statement>
        <rationale>Version history provides the audit trail and historical context for disputes over ownership.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pair RACI with an escalation path: "If A is unavailable >24h, escalation owner is X."</statement>
        <rationale>Clear escalation paths prevent decision paralysis during absences.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For agent-driven projects, declare which rows the agent is "R" on and which require human "A" sign-off.</statement>
        <rationale>Explicit boundaries prevent scope creep on agent authority and clarify when human judgment is required.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/raci-lint.py" purpose="Lint a Markdown RACI table; exit 1 on validation failures (missing A, missing R, too many C)."/>
      <template path="templates/raci-template.md" purpose="Blank RACI matrix with role columns and task rows ready to fill."/>
    </templates>

